MENINGITIS, MENINGOCOCCAL - USA (04): (CALIFORNIA) FATAL, MEN WHO HAVE SEX WITH MEN, VACCINATION, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*************************************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 2 Apr 2014
Source: Los Angeles Daily News [edited]
http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20140402/8-people-in-los-angeles-county-diagnosed-with-invasive-meningococcal-disease


A total of 8 people in Los Angeles County [California] have been diagnosed with invasive meningococcal disease (IMD) this year [2014], health officials announced today [2 Apr 2014] as they issued a call for gay men to be vaccinated against the potentially fatal ailment.

According to the county Department of Public Health (DPH), 3 of the 8 patients either lived or were known to socialize in the West Hollywood or North Hollywood areas. The county plans to offer free vaccinations to people without health insurance beginning tomorrow [3 Apr 2014].

Dr. Jonathan Fielding, head of the county health department, said men who have sex with other men (MSM) should be vaccinated -- especially those who find partners online or who share cigarettes, marijuana or illegal drugs.

Of the 8 cases reported in the county, 4 involved MSM, including 3 who were HIV-positive, according to the county.

County DPH officials consulted with state health experts and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), and they recommended vaccinations for all MSM, regardless of whether they consider themselves gay or bisexual, and regardless of their HIV status.

Health officials noted that the risk of contracting IMD is low among the general population, noting that the bacteria is less contagious than viruses that cause the flu. Activities that can put people at risk of the disease include: smoking, including marijuana, cigarettes and hookah; close contact with an infected person, including sharing beverages or cigarettes, kissing and coughing; and staying in group settings such as dorms, jails or shelters for extended periods.

The infection can cause brain damage, hearing loss or potentially death. Symptoms can include fever, stiff neck, skin rash, severe headaches, low blood pressure and muscle pain. The disease spreads quickly, so fast diagnosis and treatment is "imperative," health officials said.

The county plans to offer free vaccines to residents without health insurance beginning tomorrow [3 Apr 2014]. A list of clinics is available by calling the county information line at 2-1-1 or online at http://publichealth.lacounty.gov/.

