******
[2]
Date: Wed 2 Apr 2014
Source: WeHo News [edited]
http://www.wehonews.com/z/wehonews/meningitis-strikes-wehonoho-gay-communities-raising-concerns/


The Los Angeles County Department of Public Health (Public Health) today [2 Apr 2014] confirmed reports of a total of 8 invasive meningococcal disease (IMD) cases in Los Angeles County in 2014. Of these 8, 4 cases were reported among men who have sex with men (MSM), including 3 men who were HIV-positive. Of those cases, 3 died. Public Health refused to provide any more information, so it remains unclear if any of the deaths were of gay men.

A vital difference between these cases and investigations of IMD in 2012 and 2013 is that distinct epidemiological commonalities were found among the 2014 MSM cases.

Of the 4 IMD cases among MSM, 3 reported either residence in, or socializing around, the West Hollywood and North Hollywood areas, and 3 were between 27-28 years of age (the 4th case was 50 years of age).

The nexus being West Hollywood and the illness extending to the HIV community raise the level of caution issued by the Public Health Department. Based on consultations with the Centers for Disease Control, Public Health recommends that all HIV positive men and men who have sex with men (MSM) get vaccinated for meningitis immediately.

"All HIV-positive MSM, and all MSM regardless of HIV status, who regularly have close or intimate contact with multiple partners, or who seek partners through the use of digital applications, particularly those who share cigarettes, marijuana or use illegal drugs, should visit their health provider to be vaccinated against invasive meningococcal disease," said Jonathan E. Fielding, MD, MPH, Director of Public Health and Health Officer. "At-risk MSM who don't have health insurance can obtain a free vaccination through the Department of Public Health."

Last year [2013] West Hollywood took a scare when a popular lawyer died hours after falling ill from the disease. Days later it was revealed that a 2nd gay man had succumbed to the disease [in December 2012, but Public Health had not made the connection between his death, meningitis and his sexual orientation until April 2013]. Still, despite the concerns expressed at the time about the potential for widespread contagion, neither man had an acquaintance or crossed paths, and no more gay men came down with the infection in the weeks following.

Public Health was slower to get off the dime than city and HIV/AIDS leaders council member John Duran and AHF [AIDS Healthcare Foundation] founder/president Michael Weinstein, however, so AHF dug into its own pockets to offer free meningitis vaccinations to the HIV and gay community, to phenomenal response. Within 3 days of offering the vaccine, AHF's outreach campaign had provided 2896 free vaccinations to the community. It also came to light that Public Health until November 2012 did not do any sexual orientation screening, but that a retroactive look for indicators had been done and found that gay men in West Hollywood/Los Angeles were not spreading the illness in larger than usual numbers.

"Most of the meningitis we see," Jonathan E. Fielding, the county director of public health said last year [2013], "is in family groups. Children, especially, spread the illness." Explaining last year that he understood the "level of concern" in the gay community, that meningitis should not be considered a "gay disease," and while meningitis is infectious, it is not as contagious as flu or the common cold, he said. Still, the community stakeholders and Public Health remain wary of large gatherings of people likely to share water bottles, cutlery or engage in deep kissing, such as [at] nightclubs.

AIDS Healthcare Foundation, which led the way to vaccinations last year [2013], will also be offering them at their Men's Wellness Center located at 1300 North Vermont Avenue, Suite 407, Los Angeles. For more information, please call (866) 339-2525 or visit http://www.aidshealth.org. The LA Gay & Lesbian Center offers meningococcal vaccine at its McDonald/Wright Building, located at 1625 North Schrader Boulevard, Los Angeles. It also offers free meningococcal vaccine at The Spot, located at 745 North San Vicente Boulevard, West Hollywood. For more information, please call (323) 860-5855 (McDonald/Wright) or (323) 993-7440 (The Spot) or visit http://www.lagaycenter.org. The Saban Community Clinic offers free meningococcal vaccine at its Hollywood-Wilshire Health Center, located at 5205 Melrose Avenue, Los Angeles. For more information, please call (323) 769-7800 or visit http://www.sabancommunityclinic.org. In West Hollywood, the MinuteClinic at CVS/pharmacy, located at 8491 Santa Monica Boulevard, offers meningococcal vaccine for a fee, though the MinuteClinic will accept health insurance coverage. For more information, please call (866) 389-2727 or visit http://www.minuteclinic.com/CA/Los-Angeles/West-Hollywood.aspx.

For more information regarding invasive meningococcal disease and vaccination, please visit http://www.cdc.gov/meningococcal/ and http://publichealth.lacounty.gov/acd/Mening.htm.

[Byline: Ryan Gierach]

